TY  - JOUR
T1  - Conservative Accounting Choices
AU  - Bagnoli, Mark
AU  - Watts, Susan G.
Y1  - 2005/05/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1040.0351
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1040.0351
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 786
EP  - 801
VL  - 51
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Managers have sufficient discretion under generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) to adopt more or less conservative financial reporting policies. In this paper, we develop a signaling model to provide insight into managers? decisions to be conservative in their accounting. We provide conditions under which the market can use the manager?s exercise of discretion to infer her private information about the future prospects of the firm and thus firm value. Under these conditions, we also show that there are meaningful differences between earnings response coefficients for firms whose managers choose a conservative reporting policy and those whose managers do not. Finally, we use our theoretical model to provide intuition for some established empirical results on earnings response coefficients.
AB  - Managers have sufficient discretion under generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) to adopt more or less conservative financial reporting policies. In this paper, we develop a signaling model to provide insight into managers? decisions to be conservative in their accounting. We provide conditions under which the market can use the manager?s exercise of discretion to infer her private information about the future prospects of the firm and thus firm value. Under these conditions, we also show that there are meaningful differences between earnings response coefficients for firms whose managers choose a conservative reporting policy and those whose managers do not. Finally, we use our theoretical model to provide intuition for some established empirical results on earnings response coefficients.
