TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the Timing of CEO Stock Option Awards
AU  - Lie, Erik
Y1  - 2005/05/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0365
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0365
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 802
EP  - 812
VL  - 51
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This study documents that the abnormal stock returns are negative before unscheduled executive option awards and positive afterward. The return pattern has intensified over time, suggesting that executives have gradually become more effective at timing awards to their advantage, and possibly explaining why the results in this study differ from those in past studies. Moreover, I document that the predicted returns are abnormally low before the awards and abnormally high afterward. Unless executives possess an extraordinary ability to forecast the future marketwide movements that drive these predicted returns, the results suggest that at least some of the awards are timed retroactively.
AB  - This study documents that the abnormal stock returns are negative before unscheduled executive option awards and positive afterward. The return pattern has intensified over time, suggesting that executives have gradually become more effective at timing awards to their advantage, and possibly explaining why the results in this study differ from those in past studies. Moreover, I document that the predicted returns are abnormally low before the awards and abnormally high afterward. Unless executives possess an extraordinary ability to forecast the future marketwide movements that drive these predicted returns, the results suggest that at least some of the awards are timed retroactively.
